"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426619","Department for Transport","false","2015-11-10","<p>The Department does not retain data on the uptake of the Cycle to Work scheme. The Scheme is an employee benefit covered by an exemption and therefore employers do not have to make an annual tax return regarding the benefit.</p><br /><p>However the Cycle to Work Alliance has published reports containing information on take up of the scheme: <a href="http://www.cycletoworkalliance.org.uk/news.html" target="_blank">http://www.cycletoworkalliance.org.uk/news.html</a>, and they state that in 2014 record numbers of employees participated in the cycle to work scheme.</p><br />","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2015-11-10T16:29:30.22Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426619/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426619/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426619/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-11-05","Cycling","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what take-up there has been of the cycle to work salary sacrifice scheme since it started.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","15103"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426620","Department for Transport","false","2015-11-10","<p>The Department for Transport currently has two Government cars available for use by its 5 Ministers.</p><br /><p>As a result of a series of changes, including closure of the Government mail service, overall operating costs have fallen from £20.956m in 2010/11 to £6.325m in 2014/15. During the same period the number of vehicles in the GCS for use by ministers have fallen from 227 to 78.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2015-11-10T13:41:44.343Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426620/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426620/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426620/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-11-05","Department for Transport: Official Cars","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will name the people in his Department who are entitled to use the Government Car Service.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","15015"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426621","Department for Transport","false","2015-11-10","<p>As at 31 March 2015 Network Rail’s Net Assets totalled £6,391 million.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2015-11-10T15:51:54.053Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426621/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426621/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426621/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-11-05","Network Rail","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the estimated value of Network Rail was on the most recent date for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","14987"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426622","Department for Transport","false","2015-11-10","<p>The Road Investment Strategy provides certainty about road investment ensuring more efficient operation and faster delivery for the English strategic road network. It sets out the vision and investment plan for a five year period from 2015 to 2020, encouraging the supply chain to invest and innovate from the long term certainty that this provides. Highways England is responsible for delivering the strategy and has been set a series of demanding targets by Government, which is regularly assessed, including independent monitoring by the Office of Rail and Road.</p><p>The combination of the measures will save the taxpayer £1.2 billion in the next 5 years and at least £2.6 billion over ten years. It also means clearer accountability and greater transparency, providing better assurance on the investment of public money.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2015-11-10T14:48:12.41Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426622/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426622/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426622/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-11-05","Productivity","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment he has made of the effect of his road investment strategy on productivity.","false","Biography information for Seema Malhotra","Feltham and Heston","Seema Malhotra","14992"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426623","Department for Transport","true","2015-11-10","<p><del class="ministerial">I am committed to ensuring that the trains enter service as planned. Contractual details regarding any compensation is commercially confidential.</del></p><p><ins class="ministerial">During the period 2009-10 to date, the following numbers of ministers have been entitled to use Government cars:</ins></p><p><ins class="ministerial"> </ins></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><ins class="ministerial">2009-10</ins></p></td><td><p><ins class="ministerial">4</ins></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><ins class="ministerial">2010-11</ins></p></td><td><p><ins class="ministerial">4</ins></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><ins class="ministerial">2011-12</ins></p></td><td><p><ins class="ministerial">4</ins></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><ins class="ministerial">2012-13</ins></p></td><td><p><ins class="ministerial">4</ins></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><ins class="ministerial">2013-14</ins></p></td><td><p><ins class="ministerial">4</ins></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><ins class="ministerial">2014-15</ins></p></td><td><p><ins class="ministerial">5</ins></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><ins class="ministerial">2015-16</ins></p></td><td><p><ins class="ministerial">5</ins></p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><ins class="ministerial"> </ins></p><p><ins class="ministerial">As a result of a series of changes, including closure of the Government mail service, overall operating costs have fallen from £20.956m in 2010/11 to £6.325m in 2014/15. During the same period the number of vehicles in the GCS for use by ministers have fallen from 227 to 78.</ins></p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2015-11-10T15:37:17.607Z","2016-03-18T13:04:04.543Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426623/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426623/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426623/answer","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426623/answer/previousversion/29560","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","27","Transport","Transport","2015-11-05","Department for Transport: Official Cars","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many people in his Department have been entitled to use the Government Car Service in each year since 2009-10.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","15016"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426624","Department for Transport","false","2015-11-10","<p><strong></strong>This information is not held. Local authorities have powers under the Road Traffic Regulation Act 1984 to make Traffic Regulation Orders and the Department for Transport is not involved in this process.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2015-11-10T17:49:10.767Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426624/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426624/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426624/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-11-05","Parking: Pedestrian Areas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many Traffic Regulation Orders have been introduced by local authorities to tackle pavement parking since 2011.","false","Biography information for Ian Austin","Dudley North","Ian Austin","15003"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426625","Wales Office","false","2015-11-10","<p>Clause 2 of the draft Wales Bill will place the existing convention that Parliament will not normally legislate with regard to devolved matters without the consent of the National Assembly for Wales on a statutory footing. The Government will continue to work with the Welsh Government to obtain the Assembly’s consent (via legislative consent motions) to legislation in devolved areas included in parliamentary Bills. Similarly,where Welsh Government is legislating in relation to the functions of reserved authorities, they should seek the consent of UK ministers, and the draft bill makes this clear.</p><p><br></p>","Preseli Pembrokeshire","Stephen Crabb",,"2015-11-10T16:54:55.41Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426625/answer","Biography information for Stephen Crabb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426625/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426625/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2015-11-05","Devolution: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, how the Government plans to monitor and enforce clause 2 of the draft Wales Bill.","false","Biography information for Nia Griffith","Llanelli","Nia Griffith","14991"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426626","Wales Office","false","2015-11-10","<p>The purpose of the reserved powers model in the draft Wales Bill is to define clearly the legislative competence reserved to the UK Parliament. At the same time, it enables the Assembly to modify the law in areas that would otherwise be reserved to enforce, or otherwise give effect to, its legislation.</p><p>It is right that this freedom should be balanced by a test to be applied when the Assembly seeks to modify the law in areas that are not devolved. For that reason the draft Bill defines the circumstances in which it can do so and the test to be applied – the test of necessity. This gives the Assembly flexibility to modify the law in areas outside devolved competence in order to enforce its legislation effectively, whilst ensuring the effect on these areas goes no further than necessary.</p><br /><p><strong></strong></p>","Preseli Pembrokeshire","Stephen Crabb",,"2015-11-10T17:05:00.693Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426626/answer","Biography information for Stephen Crabb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426626/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426626/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2015-11-05","Devolution: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, for what reasons the draft Wales Bill would seek to change the criteria on which the Assembly could legislate outside its normal competence, as set out in section 108(5) of the Government of Wales Act 2006.","false","Biography information for Nia Griffith","Llanelli","Nia Griffith","14989"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426627","Wales Office","false","2015-11-10","<p>The current conferred powers model of Welsh devolution sets out what an Assembly Act can do. In contrast, a reserved powers model need only set out what an Assembly Act cannot do. Under the draft Wales Bill an Assembly Act would be able to include any provision that is not outside the Assembly’s legislative competence. The wording is not therefore needed.</p>","Preseli Pembrokeshire","Stephen Crabb",,"2015-11-10T16:56:45.14Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426627/answer","Biography information for Stephen Crabb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426627/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426627/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2015-11-05","Devolution: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, with reference to the draft Wales Bill, for what reason it is his policy to remove the wording of the Government of Wales Act 2006 which states that an Act of the Assembly may make any provision that could be made by an Act of Parliament.","false","Biography information for Nia Griffith","Llanelli","Nia Griffith","14990"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426628","Wales Office","false","2015-11-13","<p>I refer the hon Member to the answer given by my Rt. Hon friend the Minister for Small Business, Industry and Enterprise (Anna Soubry) on 11 November 2015.</p>","Preseli Pembrokeshire","Stephen Crabb",,"2015-11-13T09:21:12.343Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426628/answer","Biography information for Stephen Crabb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426628/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426628/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2015-11-05","Wales Office: EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, which regulations his Department introduced as a result of EU legislation in (a) 2013, (b) 2014 and (c) 2015 to date; which regulations his Department expects to implement as a result of EU legislation in (i) 2016 and (ii) 2017; and what estimate he has made of the cost of such regulation to the (A) public purse and (B) private sector.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","15128"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426629","Women and Equalities","false","2015-11-13","<p>I refer my hon. Friend to the reply given to Parliamentary Question <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2015-11-05/15037/" target="_blank">15037</a> on 11 November 2015.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2015-11-13T14:45:25.473Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426629/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426629/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426629/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2015-11-05","Government Equalities Office: EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, which regulations the Government Equalities Office introduced as a result of EU legislation in (a) 2013, (b) 2014 and (c) 2015 to date; which regulations her Office expects to implement as a result of EU legislation in (i) 2016 and (ii) 2017; and what estimate she has made of the cost of such regulation to the (A) public purse and (B) private sector.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","15129"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426630","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-11-13","<p>All regulations implementing EU legislation that have been introduced since 2013 and their associated impacts can be found on www.legislation.gov.uk. The impact of future regulations that implement EU legislation will also be available on this site in due course.</p><br />","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2015-11-13T11:35:45.93Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426630/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426630/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426630/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-11-05","Department for Work and Pensions: EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, which regulations his Department introduced as a result of EU legislation in (a) 2013, (b) 2014 and (c) 2015 to date; which regulations his Department expects to implement as a result of EU legislation in (i) 2016 and (ii) 2017; and what estimate he has made of the cost of such regulation to the (A) public purse and (B) private sector.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","15130"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426631","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-11-11","<p>The information you have requested is not currently available. The Department published its strategy for releasing official statistics on Universal Credit (UC) in September 2013. As outlined in the strategy, officials are currently quality assuring data for UC therefore it is not yet possible to give a definitive list of what statistics will be provided in the future. These statistics however will be published in accordance with the relevant protocols in the Code of Practice for official statistics.</p><p>The latest official experimental statistics on UC and the Departments release strategy can be found at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/universal-credit-statistics" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/universal-credit-statistics</a>.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel","14999 ; 15072 ; 15074 ; 15075 ; 15076 ; 15078 ; 15079 ; 15080 ; 15082 ; 15085","2015-11-11T15:43:21.713Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426631/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426631/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426631/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-11-05","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what the average reduction in entitlement to universal credit was which resulted from a claimant taking up paid work in the most recent month for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","15077"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426632","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-11-10","<p>The Department does not publish full-year forecast DEL spending. Instead, at the end of the financial year, the Annual Report and Accounts will be published detailing outturn spending.</p><p><strong>AME Forecasts</strong></p><p>a) Summer Budget 2015 (and current forecast)<br> <strong>£170,577m (nominal terms)</strong><br><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/benefit-expenditure-and-caseload-tables-2015" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/benefit-expenditure-and-caseload-tables-2015</a><br>Workbook: Outturn and forecast: Summer Budget 2015<br>Table 1a cell BS84</p><p>b) March Budget 2015<br> <strong>£170,274 (nominal terms)</strong><br><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/benefit-expenditure-and-caseload-tables-2015" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/benefit-expenditure-and-caseload-tables-2015</a><br>Workbook: Outturn and forecast: March Budget 2015<br>Table 1a - cell BS84</p><p>Summer Budget 2015 is the current forecast for 2015-16. This will be updated for Autumn Statement 2015</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2015-11-10T15:26:10.453Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426632/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426632/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426632/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-11-05","Department for Work and Pensions: Public Expenditure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate he has made of his Department's expected DEL underspend in 2015-16; what his Department's current forecast for AME expenditure is in 2015-16; and what that forecast was at the time of (a) the Summer Budget 2015 and (b) the March Budget 2015.","false","Biography information for Owen Smith","Pontypridd","Owen Smith","15187"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426633","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-11-10","<p>People with disabilities are entitled to an extra bedroom for non-resident overnight carers and disabled children who are unable to share with another child.</p><br /><p>Since 2013, we have provided local authorities with £470 million in Discretionary Housing Payments funding. This has enabled local authorities to give additional support to claimants where appropriate. This includes £175 million specifically for those affected by the removal of the spare room subsidy, of which £75 million is for those living in significantly adapted properties.</p><br /><p>We will continue to provide additional support through Discretionary Housing Payments and have made a further £800 million in DHP funding available for the next 5 years of this Parliament.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2015-11-10T15:34:28.797Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426633/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426633/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426633/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-11-05","Housing Benefit: Social Rented Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment he has made of the effect of the under-occupancy penalty on people with disabilities.","false","Biography information for Owen Smith","Pontypridd","Owen Smith","15144"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426634","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-11-10","<p>Current numbers of people affected by this measure can be found using the following link to Stat-Xpore:</p><p><a href="https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/" target="_blank">https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/</a></p><br /><p>Following on from the 2012 impact assessment an independent two year evaluation was commissioned that looked at the effects of this policy. The interim report was published last July and the final report is due to be published before the end of the year.</p><br /><p>A link to the interim evaluation can be found below:-</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/329948/rr882-evaluation-of-removal-of-the-spare-room-subsidy.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/329948/rr882-evaluation-of-removal-of-the-spare-room-subsidy.pdf</a></p><br /><p>The full report will be published by the end of the year.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2015-11-10T14:13:34.9Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426634/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426634/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426634/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-11-05","Housing Benefit: Social Rented Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what recent assessment he has made of the number of people who have been affected by the under-occupancy penalty.","false","Biography information for Owen Smith","Pontypridd","Owen Smith","15145"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426635","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-11-11","<p>The information you have requested is not currently available. The Department published its strategy for releasing official statistics on Universal Credit (UC) in September 2013. As outlined in the strategy, officials are currently quality assuring data for UC therefore it is not yet possible to give a definitive list of what statistics will be provided in the future. These statistics however will be published in accordance with the relevant protocols in the Code of Practice for official statistics.</p><p>The latest official experimental statistics on UC and the Departments release strategy can be found at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/universal-credit-statistics" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/universal-credit-statistics</a>.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel","14999 ; 15072 ; 15074 ; 15076 ; 15077 ; 15078 ; 15079 ; 15080 ; 15082 ; 15085","2015-11-11T15:43:20.25Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426635/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426635/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426635/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-11-05","Universal Credit: Self-employed","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many self-employed people in receipt of universal credit reported earnings lower than the minimum income floor in the most recent month for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","15075"
