"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426087","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-11-10","<p>The Government is committed to securing an ambitious, legally binding, global deal on climate change at the United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change (UNFCCC) Conference of the Parties (COP) 21 in Paris, in December.</p><br /><p>My Right Hon. Friend the Secretary of State for Climate and Energy, is taking every opportunity to press for an agreement that secures ambitious mitigation commitments from all Parties that together keep the goal of limiting global warming to below 2 degrees within reach. We also want an agreement that includes a regular review of targets to increase ambition over time, a global long term goal and a robust, legally binding framework to ensure transparency and accountability of commitments to help the world track progress.</p><br /> <br />","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2015-11-10T15:47:18.85Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426087/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426087/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426087/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-11-04","Carbon Emissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what steps she is taking to prevent carbon emissions outside the UK.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","14808"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426088","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-11-13","<p>Protecting forests delivers substantial climate, development, biodiversity and ecosystem outcomes. Stopping deforestation offers the potential to reduce greenhouse gas emissions on a globally significant scale, while protecting the vital services, such as regulating rainfall patterns, on which the world economy depends for agricultural productivity and sustainable economic growth.</p><br /><p>Addressing deforestation and supporting the sustainable management of forests is a priority for the UK’s £3.87 billion International Climate Fund (ICF), and the Prime Minister announced in September that this will rise to £5.8bn over the next Spending review period. To date, over £700m has been programmed, including initiatives that: incentivise action to reduce deforestation and forest degradation; support forest management, governance and market reforms; curb illegal and unsustainable use of forest resources; and promote investments in sustainable forestry, agriculture and land management.</p><br /><p>The UK also plays an active leadership role in international fora, including the United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change, the Convention on Biodiversity, and the United Nations Forum on Forests. Last year, we played a key role in the negotiation of the New York Declaration on Forests, which set ambitious targets for halving (by 2020) and halting (by 2030) the loss of natural forests, eliminating deforestation from the production of key agricultural commodities by 2020, and accelerating restoration efforts.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2015-11-13T12:25:14.113Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426088/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426088/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426088/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-11-04","Forests: Sustainable Development","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what steps she is taking to support the sustainable management of forests outside the UK.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","14809"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426089","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-11-10","<p>The Government supports the view that the Paris Agreement should set out a long term direction for all countries and the international community on adaptation, which should encourage all countries to reduce vulnerability to the impacts of climate change and strengthen resilience, in order to enable climate resilient sustainable development.</p><p><br></p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2015-11-10T16:02:47.047Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426089/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426089/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426089/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-11-04","Climate Change Convention: Paris","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, if she will take steps in support of the African Group's agreement on a Global Goal for Adaptation at the Paris Climate Conference in December.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","14810"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426090","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-11-16","<p>The ONS will publish estimates of the number of people directly employed in the low carbon economy in December 2015. Notwithstanding this, the Government’s commitment to low carbon infrastructure helps support many thousands of highly skilled jobs across the economy. For example, the proposed new nuclear power station at Hinkley Point C is estimated to support around 25,000 jobs, of which 7,000 are local. Similarly, the two Siemens offshore wind facilities in Hull announced in 2014 are estimated to support 1,000 direct jobs and 300 construction jobs. Internationally, low carbon strategies and potential jobs that arise from them will be guided by countries’ delivery of their intended contributions to a global climate change agreement. The UKis committed to supporting the world’s poorest to become more resilient to the effects of a changing climate and to take the clean energy path to growth and prosperity. Its international climate finance has helped support the creation of 39,000 jobs in developing countries up to April this year in relation to low carbon climate resilience.</p><br />","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2015-11-16T14:16:57.707Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426090/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426090/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426090/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-11-04","Environment Protection: Job Creation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what steps she is taking to support the creation of jobs through low carbon growth (a) within and (b) outside the UK.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","14956"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426091","Home Office","false","2015-11-17","<p>UK Visas and Immigration (UKVI) can confirm that it corresponds with hon. Members through informal channels such as email and telephone wherever possible as opposed to formal written correspondence.</p><p>A recent MP satisfaction survey conducted by UKVI revealed that over 87% of respondents prefer informal channels of communication such as email or telephone rather than a formal letter response. This effective channel shift has improved the level of service that the department has provided to MPs.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2015-11-17T17:18:04.397Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426091/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426091/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426091/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-11-04","Home Office: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what representations she has received on responding to correspondence from hon. Members by email rather than by letter.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","14891"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426092","Home Office","false","2015-11-09","<p>The systems used to manage correspondence received from hon. Members do not record whether the response has been sent by email or letter; we are therefore unable to provide the requested breakdown or associated costs.</p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2015-11-09T17:35:34.58Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426092/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426092/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426092/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-11-04","Home Office: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many replies to constituent correspondence from hon. Members her Department sent by (a) email and (b) letter in each of the last three years; and what the cost of using each method was in each such year.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","14880"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426093","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-11-10","<p>We have received representations from a small number of hon. Members and where appropriate the Department obliges with email replies. Where there is sensitive personal information in a reply, it will be posted for security reasons.</p><p>The cost differential between sending postal replies and email replies is minimal.</p><p>The exact information requested on the method of dispatch is not available other than at a disproportionate cost.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","14890","2015-11-10T16:14:23.147Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426093/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426093/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426093/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-11-04","Department for Work and Pensions: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many replies to constituent correspondence from hon. Members his Department sent by (a) email and (b) letter in each of the last three years; and what the cost breakdown of each method was in each such year.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","14881"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426094","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-11-10","<p>We have received representations from a small number of hon. Members and where appropriate the Department obliges with email replies. Where there is sensitive personal information in a reply, it will be posted for security reasons.</p><p>The cost differential between sending postal replies and email replies is minimal.</p><p>The exact information requested on the method of dispatch is not available other than at a disproportionate cost.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","14881","2015-11-10T16:14:23.223Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426094/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426094/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426094/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-11-04","Department for Work and Pensions: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what representations he has received on responding to correspondence from hon. Members by email rather than by letter.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","14890"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426095","Department of Health","false","2015-11-10","<p>Providing the requested information would involve analysis of each grant awarded and would therefore be at disproportionate cost. There is a range of different circumstances where it would not be appropriate or value for money to run a competed scheme.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2015-11-10T16:49:00.817Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426095/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426095/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426095/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-11-04","Department of Health: Grants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to the Answer of 22 October 2015 to Question 11792, which grants made under section 64 of the Health Services and Public Health Act 1964 are awarded on a non-competed basis; and if he will ensure that all future section 64 grants are awarded on a competed basis.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","14761"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426096","Department of Health","false","2015-11-11","<p>There is no requirement to commission an independent review as the award of Section 64 grants to Action on Smoking and Health has followed the appropriate policies and procedures applicable to all Section 64 grants.</p><br /><p>The assessment of the grant application for funding from Action on Smoking and Health is undertaken by members of the Tobacco Control policy team.</p><br /><p>The assessment process is the same for all grants awarded under Section 64 powers. The assessment process uses standard business case criteria and consists of a Strategic Case, Economic Case, Financial Case, Commercial Case and Project Governance.</p><br /><p>The assessment is reviewed by the Department’s Voluntary Sector Grants Hub to ensure that the grant proposal is affordable within Departmental budgets; relevant Efficiency Review Group Controls have been considered; the grant has been assessed as delivering value for money and the grant is considered to be appropriate for the Grant funding route rather than procurement.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2015-11-11T09:57:09.567Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426096/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426096/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426096/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-11-04","Action on Smoking and Health","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to the Answer of 28 October 2015 to Question 12657, if he will commission an independent review into the procedures followed by the Tobacco Control policy team within his Department when awarding section 64 grants to Action on Smoking and Health.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","14760"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426097","Department of Health","false","2015-11-10","<p>It is normal practice for Departmental officials to discuss grant applications with the applicant. The application process is iterative to ensure the final objectives are in line with Departmental aims.</p><p><strong></strong></p><p>We have received additional information from Action on Smoking and Health about its grant application for the 2015-16 financial year since receipt of that application, as part of this process.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2015-11-10T16:41:14.447Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426097/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426097/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426097/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-11-04","Action on Smoking and Health","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what representations his Department received from Action on Smoking and Health about its grant application for the 2015-16 financial year since receipt of that application.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","14762"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426098","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-11-10","<p>The requested information as of September 2012, 2013 and 2014 is within the table below:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><strong>Country</strong></td><td><strong>Sept-12</strong></td><td><strong>Sept-13</strong></td><td><strong> Sept-14</strong></td></tr><tr><td>GB</td><td>8,300</td><td>9,000</td><td>9,700</td></tr><tr><td>Overseas</td><td>600</td><td>1,000</td><td>1,000</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Total</strong></td><td><strong>8,900</strong></td><td><strong>10,000</strong></td><td><strong>10,700</strong></td></tr></tbody></table><p>“-“ indicates less than 100</p><p>Source:<br>DWP 5% data</p><p>Notes:<br>1. Figures are rounded to the nearest 100. Totals may not sum due to rounding</p><p>2. Cases where the payment has been suspended or the payment is not “live” have been omitted from these figures.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2015-11-10T16:34:17.647Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426098/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426098/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426098/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-11-04","State Retirement Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people over 100 years old living (a) in the UK and (b) overseas received the state pension in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","14680"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426099","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-11-12","<p>The Royal Prerogative of Mercy can only be exercised following a conviction. Moussa Koussa has never been convicted of any offence in the UK, therefore the question of the Royal Prerogative of Mercy has never arisen.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2015-11-12T13:04:05.343Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426099/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426099/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426099/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-11-04","Moussa Koussa: Prerogative of Mercy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, whether the Royal Prerogative of Mercy has been granted to Moussa Koussa; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Kate Hoey","Vauxhall","Kate Hoey","14895"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426100","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-11-12","<p>Moussa Koussa flew to the UK from Tunisia of his own volition, having notified our authorities shortly before his departure of his intention to travel here.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2015-11-12T15:07:22.117Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426100/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426100/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426100/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-11-04","Moussa Koussa","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, whether Moussa Koussa's arrival in the UK by aeroplane at Farnborough in March 2011 was by prior agreement with the UK Government; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Kate Hoey","Vauxhall","Kate Hoey","14953"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426101","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-11-12","<p>The bombing of Pan Am flight 103 over Lockerbie remains the subject of an open investigation led by the Crown Office and Procurator Fiscal Service (the Scottish Prosecution Service) and the Police Service of Scotland. The details of that investigation are a matter for those authorities.</p><p>Helping the police take forward their investigation is a priority. We continue to provide them whatever support we can. However, the worsening of the security and political situation in Libya has practically stalled effective engagement. Scottish investigators will continue to develop the elements of their investigation that do not require them to travel to Libya. Once stability returns efforts will be made at the earliest and safe opportunity to re-commence the co-operation.</p><br />","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2015-11-12T13:12:11.197Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426101/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426101/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426101/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-11-04","Moussa Koussa","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what evidence the Government holds of involvement in the Lockerbie bombing of Moussa Koussa; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Kate Hoey","Vauxhall","Kate Hoey","14952"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426102","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-11-12","<p>Jonathan Dart commenced his duties in December 2014. There was no official announcement or notification. Mr. Dart continues to engage widely with victims and victims’ representatives.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2015-11-12T13:10:09.73Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426102/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426102/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426102/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-11-04","Libya: Terrorism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, when Jonathan Dart commenced his duties as head of the Libyan Reconciliation Unit; when lawyers representing victims of terrorist attacks committed using Semtex supplied by Libya were advised of his appointment; on what dates Mr Dart met those lawyers (a) first and (b) subsequently; and what other contact Mr Dart has had with those lawyers.","false","Biography information for Kate Hoey","Vauxhall","Kate Hoey","14951"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426103","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-11-12","<p>There has been no contact between Government officials and Moussa Koussa since his departure from the UK in 2011.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2015-11-12T13:06:04.893Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426103/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426103/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426103/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-11-04","Moussa Koussa","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what contact there has been between Government officials and Moussa Koussa since his departure from the UK in 2011; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Kate Hoey","Vauxhall","Kate Hoey","14947"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426104","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-11-12","<p>Between 2002 and October 2011 the Government funded visits to Libya for current officials and Ministers as part of regular diplomatic relations.</p><p>No retired civil servants or former ministers visited Libya at public expense</p><br />","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2015-11-12T13:07:24.18Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426104/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426104/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426104/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-11-04","Libya: Diplomatic Relations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, which (a) retired civil servants and (b) former Ministers travelled to Libya at public expense between 2002 and October 2011; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Kate Hoey","Vauxhall","Kate Hoey","14948"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426105","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-11-12","<p>Since 2011, the Government has funded visits to Libya by current officials and Ministers as part of regular diplomatic relations. In addition, in periods when the security situation in Libya permitted it, a number of visits to Libya, including by Jonathan Powell the Prime Minister’s Envoy to Libya, have been funded by HMG.</p><p>No retired civil servants or former ministers have visited Libya at public expense.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2015-11-12T13:08:54.163Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426105/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426105/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426105/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-11-04","Libya: Diplomatic Relations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, which (a) retired civil servants and (b) former Ministers have travelled to Libya at public expense since October 2011; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Kate Hoey","Vauxhall","Kate Hoey","14949"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426106","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-11-12","<p>It has been the policy of successive governments not to comment on meetings involving intelligence officials.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2015-11-12T13:29:16.067Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426106/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426106/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426106/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-11-04","Moussa Koussa","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what was discussed at the meeting between Sir John Scarlett and Moussa Koussa in the UK in 2001.","false","Biography information for Kate Hoey","Vauxhall","Kate Hoey","14950"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426107","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-11-12","<p>Moussa Koussa has received no payments from HMG.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2015-11-12T13:13:44.603Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426107/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426107/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426107/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-11-04","Moussa Koussa","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what (a) ex gratia and (b) other payments were made to Moussa Koussa by the UK Government in 2011; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Kate Hoey","Vauxhall","Kate Hoey","14954"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426108","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-11-12","<p>Mr Koussa's entry into Doha was a matter for him and the Qatari authorities.</p><p>No elements of Moussa Koussa's travel to Qatar were paid for by the UK Government.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2015-11-12T13:14:55.5Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426108/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426108/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426108/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-11-04","Moussa Koussa","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what costs relating to the relocation of Moussa Koussa to Qatar in 2011 were met by the UK Government; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Kate Hoey","Vauxhall","Kate Hoey","14955"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426109","Department for Education","false","2015-11-09","<p>Information on the destinations of Key Stage 4 and Key Stage 5 students was published on 20 October 2015. These experimental statistics are available online.[1]</p><p>The statistics are published at national, local, constituency, and institution level.Since they were first released in 2012, we have added data about employment destinations; improved the coverage by including independent schools, special schools, pupil referral units and other alternative provision; and have improved the timeliness of the data. We have also included the Key Stage 4 education destinations in performance tables.</p><p>We are looking to improve the quality of the destinations data by linking it to employment and benefits data. We plan to publish all Key Stage 4 and Key Stage 5 destinations as headline performance measures in the 2016 performance tables.</p><p>In our guidance on post-16 funding, we set out the expectation that providers of post-16 education and training will add information on their Government funded courses to a national database. The aim is that portal providers will be able to access this information and present it in a user-friendly way, to help young people make informed decisions about their options. Providers of post-16 education and training are currently uploading course information to this database.</p><br /><p>[1] <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/statistics-destinations" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/statistics-destinations</a></p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2015-11-09T16:34:16.87Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426109/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426109/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426109/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-11-04","School Leaving","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps the Government has taken to (a) improve destination data for school leavers and (b) develop online portals to help advise school leavers of all post-16 learning options.","false","Biography information for Seema Malhotra","Feltham and Heston","Seema Malhotra","14828"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426110","HM Treasury","false","2015-11-09","<p>The link between productivity as measured by wage returns and higher education is well established. Academic evidence shows that a woman can expect on average to earn £252,000 more over their lifetime after studying at university, net of taxes and loan repayments. For a man the equivalent figure is £168,000. This government believes that people from all backgrounds should be able to benefit from a university education. UCAS data suggests that those from disadvantaged areas are 38% more likely to apply to university now than they were in 2009.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2015-11-09T14:38:32.7Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426110/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426110/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426110/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-11-04","Higher Education: Productivity","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what evidential basis there is for there being a link between enabling students from low and middle income backgrounds to attend university and improving UK productivity set out in his report, Fixing the foundations: Creating a more prosperous nation, published in July 2015.","false","Biography information for Seema Malhotra","Feltham and Heston","Seema Malhotra","14827"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426111","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-11-09","<p>Opening up the higher education sector to new high quality providers will encourage diversity and competition to help drive up the quality of teaching and, in turn, the contribution of graduates to the economy. Further details on these proposals are set out in my Department’s Green Paper “<a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/474266/BIS-15-623-fulfilling-our-potential-teaching-excellence-social-mobility-and-student-choice-accessible.pdf" target="_blank">Fulfilling our Potential: Teaching Excellence, Social Mobility and Student Choice</a>” published on 6 November.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2015-11-09T15:50:36.833Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426111/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426111/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426111/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-11-04","Degrees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how the introduction of a faster route to degree-awarding powers set out in the HM Treasury report, Fixing the foundations: Creating a more prosperous nation, published in July 2015, will improve UK productivity.","false","Biography information for Seema Malhotra","Feltham and Heston","Seema Malhotra","14829"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426112","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-11-09","<p>Over time the further education funding system has become complicated, with a lengthy set of rules about who and what can be funded. We plan to significantly simplify this funding system and at the same time increase local influence over the skills system so funding can be used to best meet local economic need. A key part of this simplification is to decouple funding and qualifications, freeing up providers and in time local commissioners to deliver the learning required to meet the skill needs of local economies and to maximise the benefit to local communities. We will include more detail on this in the Skills Funding Letter for 2016-17.</p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2015-11-09T14:45:40.563Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426112/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426112/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426112/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-11-04","Adult Education: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what plans the Government has to move away from the funding per qualification model for adult learners as set out in the HM Treasury report, Fixing the foundations: Creating a more prosperous nation, published in July 2015; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Seema Malhotra","Feltham and Heston","Seema Malhotra","14826"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426113","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-11-13","<p>Local Authorities have the responsibility for creating the official street naming and numbering under the Towns Improvement Clauses Act 1847 and Public Health Act 1925. Royal Mail has the responsibility under its Universal Service obligations to create the postal address for each home and business in the UK. In creating the postal address Royal Mail utilises the official street name and number where appropriate and adds a number of additional address elements, including the postcode, which forms the basis of the Royal Mail distribution network. Royal Mail also pays Local Authorities £1 per new address that it receives from local authorities. Royal Mail compiles the list of postal addresses in to the Postcode Address File (PAF).</p><br /><p>The intellectual property rights over the data contained in the PAF, which occurs once the data is in the PAF format, belongs to Royal Mail as owners and maintainers of the PAF.</p><br /><p>In 2015, the public sector licence agreement was introduced which gives Local Authorities, Central Government, Emergency Services and Health, free access to the PAF.</p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2015-11-13T14:17:07.22Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426113/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426113/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426113/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-11-04","Royal Mail","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, pursuant to the Answer of 12 October 2015 to Question 11315, whether local authorities (a) retain intellectual property rights over the postal addresses they have helped to create and (b) benefit financially from those rights from Royal Mail.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","14730"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426114","Department for Education","false","2015-11-09","<p>16-19 funding is that it is based on the level of recruitment institutions delivered in the previous year. That means institutions’ funding keeps pace with changing student numbers with the minimum delay. The Government has no plans to change the 16-19 funding system.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2015-11-09T16:33:25.12Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426114/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426114/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426114/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-11-04","Further Education: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what assessment she has made of the effect of annual funding cycles on the ability of further education and sixth form colleges to undertake financial planning; what discussions she has had with Cabinet colleagues on that matter; what plans the Government has to change those funding cycles to reflect Government spending review cycles; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","14932"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426115","Department for Education","false","2015-11-09","<p>Our FE Workforce Strategy[1], published in 2014, sets out the steps the government has taken to encourage more Mathematics and English teachers to take up posts in further education colleges.</p><p>Since 2013, bursaries of up to £25,000 have been available to attract new graduates with relevant degrees to teach Maths and English, and to specialise in teaching students with SEN within the FE sector. These bursaries match those offered to trainee secondary teachers. To date, over 950 bursaries have been provided to graduates.</p><p>In March 2015, the Prime Minister announced an investment of £67m in a package of measures to improve the teaching of STEM subjects, including Maths, in secondary schools and sixth form colleges. This will see an additional 2,500 new Maths and Physics teachers trained, and a further 15,000 teachers given additional support to improve their subject knowledge.</p><br /><p>[1] <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/further-education-workforce-strategy" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/further-education-workforce-strategy</a></p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2015-11-09T14:18:33.06Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426115/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426115/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426115/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-11-04","Teachers: English Language and Mathematics","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps her Department is taking to increase the number of English and mathematics teachers in further education and sixth form colleges; and what effect those steps have had.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","14933"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426116","Department for Education","false","2015-11-09","<p>Ministers and officials at both the Department for Education and the Department for Business, Innovation and Skills have on-going discussions with stakeholder organisations and colleges about the need to ensure well qualified and skilled teachers of English and mathematics in both FE colleges and sixth form colleges, as we set out in our FE Workforce Strategy and National College for Teaching and Leadership business plan.</p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2015-11-09T14:15:57.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426116/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426116/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426116/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-11-04","Teachers: English Language and Mathematics","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what representations she has received on increasing the number of English and mathematics teachers in further education and sixth form colleges.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","14934"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426117","Department for Education","false","2015-11-10","<p>The Education Funding Agency (EFA) regularly assesses the financial viability of sixth-form colleges on behalf of the department. Those assessments take account of all income and costs for colleges, including costs relating to VAT and pension liabilities.</p><p>The department estimates that VAT accounts for about 3% of sixth form colleges’ expenditure each year.</p><br /><p>With regards to pension costs, sixth-form colleges may contribute to a number of pension schemes. The SFC financial returns are available online at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/sfa-financial-management-college-accounts" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/sfa-financial-management-college-accounts</a> and show employer contributions to pensions. The EFA does not routinely collect data on the cost of other pension schemes through financial returns.</p><br /> <br /> <br />","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2015-11-10T16:01:11.603Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426117/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426117/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426117/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-11-04","Sixth Form Colleges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what assessment she has made of the effect on the financial sustainability of sixth form colleges of (a) VAT and (b) pension costs; and if she will estimate the average proportion of a sixth form college's budget which is spent on those costs.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","14892"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426118","Department of Health","false","2015-11-09","<p>Some NHS Help with Health Costs claim forms, for example HC5 refund claim forms, have been amended to include a specific tick box to enable Universal Credit recipients to claim entitlement.</p><br /><p>Form HC1 (NHS Low Income Scheme application form) has been amended to include a sentence about Universal Credit, to advise those applying that until 31 October 2015, anyone in receipt of Universal Credit does not need to complete the form, as they will already be entitled to Help with Health Costs.</p><br /><p>Other forms, including: NHS prescription forms (FP10); dental treatment claim forms (FP17) and claims for NHS funded sight tests (GOS 1) and for vouchers for glasses or contact lenses (GOS 3) will be amended to include a Universal Credit box in due course.</p><br /><p>A patient can make a claim for entitlement by ticking the “gets income based Jobseekers Allowance” on relevant forms. Guidance for both the public and healthcare practitioners (such as pharmacists, dentist and opticians) has been included on NHS Choices with links from the Universal Credit webpages on Gov.uk.</p><br />","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2015-11-09T17:21:51.883Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426118/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426118/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426118/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-11-04","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether NHS charges claim forms include a box for universal credit.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","14935"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426119","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-11-12","<p>The UK deplores the treatment of the Rohingya community in Rakhine State, who are subject to persecution and denied the most basic rights. We welcome the work of the highly effective UN Special Rapporteur on Burma, who has shone a spotlight on violations against the Rohingya in Rakhine. She has not characterised the treatment of the Rohingya as genocide, and neither did the UN Special Adviser on the Prevention of Genocide in his 4 November statement on Burma’s elections. However, any judgement on whether genocide has occurred is a matter for international judicial decision, rather than for governments or non-judicial bodies. A UN investigation would require high level international support for which, we assess, there is little prospect of agreement at this stage. Our approach is to seek an end to all violations, irrespective of whether or not they fit the definition of specific international crimes. I and other British Government Ministers take every appropriate opportunity, both publicly and in private, to press the Burmese authorities to take urgent steps to address the situation of the Rohingya. I did this with senior Burmese Ministers during my visit to Burma in July, when I travelled to Rakhine State for the second time. Most recently, I raised the issue with the Burmese Foreign Minister, Wunna Maung Lwin, in September in New York. After the 8 November elections, the UK will continue our efforts to address the serious ongoing human rights violations against the Rohingya in Rakhine State.</p>","East Devon","Mr Hugo Swire",,"2015-11-12T17:40:32.237Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426119/answer","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426119/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426119/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-11-04","Burma: Rohingya","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, if he will support the establishment of a full, international, independent investigation by the UN into claims of genocide against the Rohingya in Burma.","false","Biography information for Mr David Burrowes","Enfield, Southgate","Mr David Burrowes","14857"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426120","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-11-13","<p>The Government would like to see UK steel companies take advantage of the commercial opportunities that a shale hydrocarbon exploration and production industry will bring. However, the decision over the use of welded steel tubes will predominantly depend on the design and specification of the well and the geology. Government officials will continue to engage with the steel industry over this large potential opportunity and will encourage it to continue its dialogue with the onshore oil and gas industry.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2015-11-13T12:24:28.21Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426120/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426120/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426120/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-11-04","Fracking: Iron and Steel","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, if she will take steps to promote the use of British welded steel instead of imported seamless steel in the shale gas exploration industry.","false","Biography information for Neil Parish","Tiverton and Honiton","Neil Parish","14676"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426121","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-11-09","<p>As at 31 October 2015, there were 869 Service and former Service personnel in receipt of Armed Forces Independence Payments.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2015-11-09T16:15:29.06Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426121/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426121/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426121/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-11-04","Armed Forces Independence Payment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many former service personnel are in receipt of Armed Forces Independence Payments.","false","Biography information for Neil Coyle","Bermondsey and Old Southwark","Neil Coyle","14797"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426122","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-11-11","<p>The Department for Work and Pensions (DWP) takes seriously any declarations of intention to attempt suicide or self harm that are made by its customers. There is a clear, detailed action plan that staff must follow if a customer declares an intention to kill or harm themselves and DWP provides guidance to help its staff deal with these incidents. The policy, procedures and guidance are reviewed regularly to ensure that they continue to meet their objectives and to identify areas for improvement.</p><p>DWP raises staff awareness through its own internal communication channels whenever guidance is reviewed and updated. This messaging ensures that related products such as learning and development for staff are also reviewed and updated concurrently.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2015-11-11T13:37:43.837Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426122/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426122/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426122/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-11-04","Jobcentre Plus: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, when his Department plans to update guidance to Jobcentre Plus staff on claimants that report suicidal thoughts; and how such existing guidance is made available to those staff.","false","Biography information for Neil Coyle","Bermondsey and Old Southwark","Neil Coyle","14716"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426123","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-11-09","<p>The information requested is not collated centrally and could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2015-11-09T14:39:44.107Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426123/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426123/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426123/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-11-04","Personal Independence Payment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what the average number of personal independence payment assessments undertaken each week was in September and October 2015.","false","Biography information for Neil Coyle","Bermondsey and Old Southwark","Neil Coyle","14734"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426124","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-11-12","<p>On 4 November, the Foreign Secretary and I met Khaled Khoja, President of the Syrian National Coalition, and Osama Abu Zayd, Spokesperson for the Free Syrian Army. The meeting was an opportunity to hear firsthand about the situation on the ground inside Syria, as well as to underline to President Khoja and his delegation the British Government’s commitment to supporting the moderate Syrian opposition in pursuit of a political solution to the conflict in Syria.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2015-11-12T13:02:50.957Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426124/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426124/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426124/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-11-04","Syria: Armed Conflict","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent contact the Government has had with the Free Syrian Army.","false","Biography information for Graham P Jones","Hyndburn","Graham Jones","14765"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426125","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-11-10","<p>As of 2 November the number of people arriving in Europe had reached 745,229 according to the UNHCR, the UN Refugee Agency. Of these 149,045 are children, including around 79,000 Syrian children. Humanitarian organisations are expecting that, given the rate of arrivals, a total of 225,000 children will need assistance between September and December 2015. All of these are considered to be vulnerable to trafficking and exploitation.</p>","Runnymede and Weybridge","Mr Philip Hammond",,"2015-11-10T15:28:35.483Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426125/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Hammond","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426125/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426125/answer","Runnymede and Weybridge","Mr Philip Hammond","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426125/answer/previousversion/28678","Biography information for Mr Philip Hammond","16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-11-04","Syria: Refugees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what estimate he has made of the number of Syrian children in Europe who are (a) vulnerable to trafficking and (b) unaccompanied.","false","Biography information for Hilary Benn","Leeds Central","Hilary Benn","14772"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426126","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-11-10","<p>With our Troika partners, the United States and Norway, we issued a statement on 6th October expressing serious concern at President Kiir’s announcement of 2nd October concerning the creation of 28 states in South Sudan, as it contradicts the Government of South Sudan’s stated commitment to implement the peace agreement. The full text of this statement can be found at:</p><p>https://www.gov.uk/government/news/south-sudan-troika-statement</p>","Runnymede and Weybridge","Mr Philip Hammond",,"2015-11-10T15:29:13.71Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426126/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Hammond","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426126/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426126/answer","Runnymede and Weybridge","Mr Philip Hammond","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426126/answer/previousversion/28682","Biography information for Mr Philip Hammond","16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-11-04","South Sudan: Politics and Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment he has made of the effect of the creation of 28 states in South Sudan on the prospects for peace in that region.","false","Biography information for Hilary Benn","Leeds Central","Hilary Benn","14773"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426127","Department for International Development","false","2015-11-09","<p>Total World Food Programme (WFP) operational requirements for 2015 are £5.23 billion. The UK is currently the second largest donor to the WFP, after the United States.As of 15 October 2015 WFP had received £2.47 billion in contributions, of which the UK provided £252.5 million.</p><br /><p>A full list of donor contributions can be found at <a href="http://www.wfp.org/funding/year/2015" target="_blank">http://www.wfp.org/funding/year/2015</a>.Very few contributions for 2016 will have been made yet, and figures for 2016 are therefore not yet available.</p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2015-11-09T16:08:35.84Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426127/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426127/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426127/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-11-04","World Food Programme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what assessment she has made of the adequacy of the financial contribution made by (a) the UK and (b) other nations to the UN World Food Programme to meet demand on that programme (i) in 2015 and (ii) from January 2016.","false","Biography information for Hilary Benn","Leeds Central","Hilary Benn","14770"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426128","Department for International Development","false","2015-11-09","<p>The World Humanitarian Summit will provide a major opportunity to set out an ambitious vision for humanitarian and development action to guide our work until 2030.</p><br /><p>The Secretary of State for International Development has four priorities for the Summit:</p><ul><li>Strengthen the protection of civilians in a crisis and improve compliance with International Humanitarian Law;</li><li>Deliver a step change in how the humanitarian community approaches resilience to natural disasters, moving from managing crises to managing risk and ensuring Governments and communities have the capacity to do this themselves;</li><li>Address the growing gap between need and available resources through smarter financing that delivers better outcomes at lower cost and is more accountable to people in need;</li><li>Focus on women and girls throughout the summit to ensure existing commitments are translated into action.</li></ul>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2015-11-09T16:01:43.177Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426128/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426128/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426128/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-11-04","Humanitarian Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what her objectives are for the World Humanitarian Summit in May 2016.","false","Biography information for Hilary Benn","Leeds Central","Hilary Benn","14771"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426129","Department for International Development","false","2015-11-09","<p>The UK is at the forefront of the response to the crisis in Syria and the region and has pledged over £1.1 billion to date, our largest ever response to a single humanitarian crisis. By the end of June 2015, our support in Syria and the region had delivered almost 20 million food rations, over 2.5 million medical consultations and relief items for 4.6 million people.</p><br /><p>Recent UN food security assessments have shown that fluctuations in assistance by the World Food Programme (WFP), as well as other agencies, has had an impact on refugee’s ability to provide for their basic needs. The UK is closely monitoring the situation across the region, alongside other key donors, to understand how this reduction in support will further impact the lives of Syrian refugees.</p><br /><p>UN appeals for Syria and the region remain severely underfunded. We continue to lobby other partners to step up to the plate and match our commitment.</p><br />","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2015-11-09T16:05:09.937Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426129/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426129/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426129/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-11-04","World Food Programme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what assessment she has made of the effect on Syrian refugees of fluctuations in the value of food vouchers provided by the World Food Programme.","false","Biography information for Hilary Benn","Leeds Central","Hilary Benn","14843"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426130","Department for Education","false","2015-11-09","<p>In the previous Parliament we allocated an extra £10.5 million to Suffolk for its schools, in the biggest step forward in fairer funding in a decade. We are protecting the schools budget in this Parliament, so that it rises with pupil numbers. We have already ensured that the extra funding for under-funded areas from 2015-16, including the £10.5 million for Suffolk, will be included in budgets for 2016-17. We are committed to going further in ensuring funding for schools in Suffolk is allocated according to need and will bring forward plans after the Spending Review.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2015-11-09T16:32:40.27Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426130/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426130/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426130/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-11-04","Schools: Suffolk","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps her Department is taking to ensure schools in rural Suffolk receive an allocation of funding based on need.","false","Biography information for Dr Dan Poulter","Central Suffolk and North Ipswich","Dr   Poulter","14777"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426131","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-11-09","<p>The Prime Minister, my right hon. Friend the Member for Witney (Mr Cameron) discussed a range of bilateral issues with President Sisi on 5 November, including our concerns about the application of laws regarding protests and counter-terrorism.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2015-11-09T15:48:55.503Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426131/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426131/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426131/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-11-04","Egypt","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions he has had with the President of Egypt on that country's protest and counter-terrorism laws.","false","Biography information for Ann Clwyd","Cynon Valley","Ann Clwyd","14837"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426132","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-11-09","<p>The Prime Minister, my right hon. Friend the Member for Witney (Mr Cameron) discussed human rights issues in Egypt with President Sisi on 5 November. He raised a number of concerns, including around the detention of political activists, mass trials and restrictions on freedom of expression.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2015-11-09T16:06:59.177Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426132/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426132/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426132/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-11-04","Egypt: Human Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what human rights concerns he plans to raise with President Abdel Fatah al-Sisi of Egypt during his forthcoming visit.","false","Biography information for Ann Clwyd","Cynon Valley","Ann Clwyd","14968"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426133","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-11-09","<p>Although the Prime Minister, my right hon. Friend the Member for Witney (Mr Cameron) did not raise this specific case on 5 November, he discussed human rights issues in Egypt with President Sisi. He raised a number of concerns, including around the detention of political activists, mass trials and restrictions on freedom of expression.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2015-11-09T15:51:44.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426133/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426133/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426133/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-11-04","Egypt: Detainees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what representations he made to the President Abdel Fatah al-Sisi of Egypt about the case of Israa Al-Taweel.","false","Biography information for Ann Clwyd","Cynon Valley","Ann Clwyd","14913"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426134","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-11-09","<p>Although the Prime Minister, my right hon. Friend the Member for Witney (Mr Cameron) did not raise this specific case on 5 November, he discussed human rights issues in Egypt with President Sisi. He raised a number of concerns, including around the detention of political activists, mass trials and restrictions on freedom of expression.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2015-11-09T15:58:12.567Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426134/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426134/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426134/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-11-04","Egypt: Detainees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, whether he raised with the President Abdel Fatah al-Sisi of Egypt the case of Mahmoud Mohamed Ahmed Hussein.","false","Biography information for Ann Clwyd","Cynon Valley","Ann Clwyd","14914"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426135","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-11-16","<p>The statutory Horserace BettingLevy Scheme does not cover offshore digital betting operators, although some operators supplement the statutory scheme with voluntarycontributions.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2015-11-16T16:58:55.483Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426135/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426135/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426135/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-11-04","Gambling: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what steps his Department is taking to secure a fair contribution from offshore digital betting operators to the 55th levy scheme.","false","Biography information for George Kerevan","East Lothian","George Kerevan","14851"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426136","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-11-16","<p>Work is continuing on the detailed policy design of the Horserace Betting Right.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2015-11-16T16:56:38.787Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426136/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426136/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426136/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-11-04","Horse Racing: Betting","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what progress he has made on and what the timescale is for implementation of a Horserace Betting Right as a replacement for the Horserace Betting Levy.","false","Biography information for George Kerevan","East Lothian","George Kerevan","14852"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426137","Wales Office","false","2015-11-09","<p><strong></strong></p><p>Clause 1 of the draft Wales Bill reflected the equivalent clause in the Scotland Bill on the date of publication. The Government will consider carefully whether any changes to the wording of the Scotland Bill clause should be reflected for Wales in the Wales Bill</p>","Preseli Pembrokeshire","Stephen Crabb",,"2015-11-09T15:42:47.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426137/answer","Biography information for Stephen Crabb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426137/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426137/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2015-11-04","Devolution: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, with reference to the Written Statement by the Secretary of State for Scotland, HCWS282 whether he plans to bring forward proposals to amend the draft Wales Bill to include a requirement that the National Assembly for Wales and the Welsh Government should not be abolished except on the basis of a decision of the people of Wales.","false","Biography information for Nia Griffith","Llanelli","Nia Griffith","14775"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426138","Wales Office","false","2015-11-11","<p>I held a large number of meetings as part of the St David’s Day process. These included meetings with the parliamentary representatives of the four main political parties in Wales to identify which Silk Commission recommendations had political consensus to be taken forward. It was agreed that discussions at these meetings would remain confidential, and the Government has no plans to publish minutes.</p><br />","Preseli Pembrokeshire","Stephen Crabb",,"2015-11-11T12:51:22.593Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426138/answer","Biography information for Stephen Crabb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426138/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426138/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2015-11-04","Devolution: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, if he will publish the minutes of all the meetings held during the St David's Day process.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Edwards","Carmarthen East and Dinefwr","Jonathan Edwards","14798"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426139","HM Treasury","false","2015-11-09","<p>This Government is committed to moving from a high welfare, high tax, low wage economy to a lower welfare, lower tax, higher wage society. As the Chancellor has made clear, the Government will set out at Autumn Statement how we plan to achieve the same goal of reforming tax credits, saving the money we need to save to secure our economy, while at the same time helping in the transition.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2015-11-09T14:44:35.283Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426139/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426139/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/426139/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-11-04","Welfare Tax Credits: Families","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Answer of 2 November 2015 to Question 13279, for what reason his Department has not estimated or calculated the number of families whose income will be reduced as a result of proposed changes to tax credits.","false","Biography information for Mr Jamie Reed","Copeland","Mr Jamie Reed","14749"
